Introduction¶

Dataset Description¶

Here is a brief explanation of the columns in the dataset.

  • PatientId - Identification of a patient
  • AppointmentID - Identification of each appointment
  • Gender - Male or Female
  • AppointmentDay - The day of the actuall appointment, when they have to visit the doctor.
  • ScheduledDay - The day someone called or registered the appointment, this is before appointment of course.
  • Age- How old is the patient.
  • Neighbourhood - Where the appointment takes place.
  • Scholarship - True of False .Scholarship indicates whether or not the patient is enrolled in Brasilian welfare program Bolsa Famlia.
  • Hipertension - True=1 or False=0
  • Diabetes - True=1 or False=0
  • Alcoholism - True=1 or False=0
  • Handcap - Level of handicap ranging from 0 - 4
  • SMS_received - Has 1 or more messages sent to the patient. True=1 or False=0
  • No-show - Yes or No. If No-show is Yes then it means appointment was missed. If No-show is No then patient made the appointment

Questions for Analysis¶

  1. What proportion of each gender missed their appointments?
  2. What month, days and periods in the time line have the highest number of No_shows?
  3. What are the top neighbourhoods with missed appointments?
  4. What are the proportions of people with health condition that miss their appoinment compared to hose that make their appointment?

def valcount_plot(col_name,df=df_cleaned):                             #define function name
    """
    This simple function plots the value counts of a speified column in a given dataframe
    column name "col_name" must be written as a string.
    default dataframe is df_cleaned
    """
    ax = sns.countplot(x=col_name, data=df)                # create countplot with just two argument (column name and dataframe)
    ax.bar_label(ax.containers[0])                  # setting bar labels
    plt.title("Value Counts of "+col_name.upper());        # Creating a related title for the plot

# Create a function to plot bar graphs of intersecion of two categorical variables
def cat_count_plot(x,hue,df=df_cleaned):
    '''
    can takes in 3 parameters.
    first 2 are required.
    The two column names as strings x  and hue.
    First column name x forms the different sections in the graph
    and second column determines the nnumber of plots per section.
    df is df_cleaned by default, but can also be specified
    '''
    ax =sns.countplot(x=x, hue=hue, data=df)
    for i in range(len(ax.containers)):
        ax.bar_label(ax.containers[i])
    plt.title(f"Count of {x} per {hue}");

4 Do health conditions make people miss their appointments?¶

I'll create a function using a modification of the previous date line plot I did here.

  • plot

    • In [83]:
    def prop_plot(col):
    """Takes one positional argument col
    col is the column name """
    
    # groupby col to see number of appointments 
    apnmnt_per_col = df_cleaned.groupby([col]).count()['no_show']
    
    # First query the data where no_show==No, then groupby col, and then get the count.
    # Here too ["age"] can be anyother column name apart from what we are grouping by
    # Which in this case is col
    made_apnmnt_per_col = df_cleaned.query("no_show == 'No'").groupby(col).count()["age"]
    # do the same for where no_show==Yes
    missed_apnmnt_per_col = df_cleaned.query("no_show == 'Yes'").groupby(col).count()["age"]
    
    # divide the counts of each category per unique value by the total count of appointments per day
    # round the values to make them look neater
    # print the results so I can know the value names directly
    made_proportions = (made_apnmnt_per_col / apnmnt_per_col).round(2)
    print(f"made_proportions\n{made_proportions}") 
    missed_proportions = (missed_apnmnt_per_col / apnmnt_per_col).round(2)
    print(f"missed_proportions\n{missed_proportions}")
    
    # create the two bars to have them in one plot
    ind = np.arange(len(made_proportions))
    width = 0.35
    made_bars = plt.bar(ind, made_proportions, width, color='g', alpha=.7, label='Made Appointment')
    missed_bars = plt.bar(ind + width, missed_proportions, width, color='r', alpha=.7, label='Missed Appointment')

    plt.ylabel('Percentage',fontsize=16) 
    plt.xlabel(col,fontsize=16)
    plt.title(f'Proportion by  and {col.upper()}and NO_SHOW')
    locations = ind + width / 2  # xtick locations
    labels = df_cleaned[col].unique()  # xtick labels
    plt.xticks(locations, labels)
    plt.legend()                         # show legend
    plt.xticks(rotation=30)              # rotating the xticks so they don't overlap
    sns.set();                           # setting to us an seaborn theme

    Conclusions¶

    1. What proportion of each gender missed their appointments?

      • The bar graphs showed that we had equal percentages of each gender missed their appointment and that females were significantly more than males.

    2. What month, days and periods in the time line have the highest number of No_shows?

      • May is the only full month hence it has significantly more appointments than the other two combined.
      • These health care centre's had a combined average of about 4308 appointments per day within the appointment dates period.
      • Tuesdays had the highest number of no_shows and had the second highest number of appointments amongst all the days of the week.

    3. What are the top neighbourhoods with missed appointments?

      • The top 20 neighboorhoods with missed appointments are largely made up of the top 20 neighbourhoods with scheduled apointments.

    4. What are the proportions of people with health condition that missed their appoinment compared to those that made their appointment?
      • The proportions of patients with particular health conditions that don't show up for an appointment are similar to the total percentage of missed appointments.

    More research can be done on how the time the appointment was scheduled affects missing or making the appointment. More explorations could have been done on age groups and health conditions, if there are any relations and how that affects the no_show column. Lastly, changing the "No", "Yes" in the no_show column to "1", "0" and then doing a correlation plot would give insight as to how the numerical features are related.

    Limitations

    A little more understanding of the geography of these neighboorhood would have helped me be able to make more group plots as plotting over 81 unique values would have been difficult to visualize. Also the time of the appointment itself ight have been more useful than the time the appointment was scheduled.
